Black Mamba rattled Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology (Jkuat) 34-12 in a Kenya Handball League clash at Nyayo Stadium. The Kaloleni-based side took a 16-5 advantage at the breather and had Martin Nguli and Morgan Juma post six goals apiece. The students, who battled from behind throughout the match had four goals from each Lewis Maraga and Dolan Bwibo. “We worked more on our defence but we need to do a lot on our attacking play. We have won four straight matches and we are on a good trajectory,” said Mamba captain Emmanuel Murangiri. Nairobi City County (NCC) overturned a 12-11 halftime deficit to defeat Technical University of Kenya (Tuk) 26-23. “We had a good game. We had good bench power and had also trained well. We followed what our coach told us and this gave us the win,” said NCC captain Nick Baraza. “However, we need to work on our shooting since most of our chances went begging.” Gibson Luyari scored eight goals while Sheldon Kisia shot four for NCC, who also suffered a 44-17 loss at the hands of Black Mamba. Ulinzi led 16-9 at the break and went on to clobber Thika 35-25. Isaac Koloi hit nine goals as Kellion Otieno added seven. The losers’ Paul Ngige managed eight. General Service Unit (GSU) slammed hapless Young City 41-20 after taking a 19-8 lead at halftime. Philip Oscar nailed nine goals, Kennedy Simiyu hit six while Kefah Masi and Simon Tenge added five each. Shamalla Danston had the losers’ nine. Strathmore University pipped Buccaneers 20-18 in a tough encounter as Maxwell Munene and Brian Murangiri bagged four goals. In other games, Strathmore nipped GSU 27-25 as Buccaneers managed a closely fought 34-31 win over Makeuni Bees. Reigning women champions Nairobi Water Queens humiliated New Hope 55-5 picking up from the break where they led 24-2. Brenda Musambai tossed in seven goals as Tracy Awino, Faith Mikhai and Michele Adhiambo recorded six each.